			<h3 id="format">Teaching format</h3>
			<p>Your biology modules are taught through a combination of:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Lectures – these larger classes provide information, stimulate thought, and suggest directions for further reading and personal study. Typical lecture sizes are between 250 to 330 students in first year, 80 to 175 students in second year, and 20 to 140 students in third year.</li> 
				<li>Seminars and tutorials - these smaller classes allow you to actively work together with your tutors and your peers to discuss topics from lectures, present papers and discuss texts and issues relevant to the course.  </li> 
				<li>Practical classes – these classes are taught in the laboratory and in the field to enabel you to learn the wide range of skills required by a modern biologist. You will be provided with teaching microscopes and taught in state-of-the-art teaching laboratories. You will also be given the opportunity to expand on your presentation and IT skills. Practical class sizes are typically between 80 to 100 students in first year, 40 to 60 students in second year, and 20 to 60 students in third year. </li>  
			</ul>
 			<p>In fourth year, modules are taught in much smaller classes of between 5 and 25 students. Fourth year also allows you to focus on a major project which occupies half of the year.  </p>  
 			<p>Outside of class, you will be expected to undertake independent work and study. This may involve, for example:</p> 
			<ul>
				<li>working on individual and group projects</li> 
				<li>undertaking research in the library or in PC classrooms</li> 
				<li>preparing coursework assignments and presentations</li> 
				<li>preparing for examinations.</li> 
			</ul>
			<h3 id="coursework-grades">Coursework and grades</h3>
			<p>During your first and second year, all modules are graded by an equal weighting of coursework and written examinations.</p>
			<p>In third year, most modules give a higher weighting to examinations.</p>  

			<p>In fourth year, some modules are entirely assessed by coursework, while others still include written examinations in addition to coursework.</p> 

			<p>Group activities may also be graded, and in this case marking methods will be communicated to you in advance.</p> 

			<p>The School of Biology aims to provide feedback on assessments and coursework within three weeks to help you improve on future assessments.</p> 

			<p>Most examinations are held at the end of the semester during a dedicated exam period. There is a dedicated revision week before exams which provides you time to prepare.</p>

			<h3 id="other-subjects">Taking other subjects</h3>
			<p>In addition to biology, you will be required to study an additional two subjects in your first year. This allows you to explore other courses of interest. In your second year, you will usually carry on at least one of these subjects. Find out more about the <a href="https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/subjects/study-options/ug/degree-routes/honours/">Honours degree structure</a>.</p>
			<p>You can also take biology as part of a joint Honours degree in which you will take core modules in two or three subjects. See more information on <a href="#joint-honours">joint options</a> below.</p>


			<h3 id="study-abroad">Study abroad</h3>
